  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Key elements typically include:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source through multiple transactions\n3. Integration: Making the money seem legitimate\n\nSpecific legal definitions vary by jurisdiction, but typically involve:\n- Intentionally hiding the origin of funds\n- Attempting to make illegal money look like legal income\n- Transforming criminal proceeds into seemingly legal assets\n\nSpecific activities can include:\n- Structuring bank deposits\n- Transferring money through multiple accounts\n- Using cash-intensive businesses\n- Creating shell companies\n\nMost countries have anti-money laundering (AML) laws that criminalize these activities, with potential penalties including:\n- Significant fines\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Imprisonment\n\nThe exact legal definitions and specifics can differ between countries and jurisdictions.",
